README.md
     1Ôćĺ# Archived project. No maintenance. 
     3ÔćĺThis project is not maintained anymore and is archived. Feel free to fork and
     4Ôćĺmake your own changes if needed. For more detail read my blog post: [Taking an indefinite sabbatical from my projects](https://arslan.io/2018/10/09/taking-an-indefinite-sabbatical-from-my-projects/)
     5Ôćĺ
     6ÔćĺThanks to everyone for their valuable feedback and contributions.
     7Ôćĺ
     8Ôćĺ# Structs
    10ÔćĺStructs contains various utilities to work with Go (Golang) structs. It was
    11Ôćĺinitially used by me to convert a struct into a `map[string]interface{}`. With
    12Ôćĺtime I've added other utilities for structs.  It's basically a high level
    13Ôćĺpackage based on primitives from the reflect package. Feel free to add new
    14Ôćĺfunctions or improve the existing code.
    15Ôćĺ
    16Ôćĺ## Install
    18Ôćĺ```bash
    19Ôćĺgo get github.com/fatih/structs
    20Ôćĺ```
    21Ôćĺ
    22Ôćĺ## Usage and Examples
    24ÔćĺJust like the standard lib `strings`, `bytes` and co packages, `structs` has
    25Ôćĺmany global functions to manipulate or organize your struct data. Lets define
    26Ôćĺand declare a struct:
    27Ôćĺ
    28Ôćĺ```go
    29Ôćĺtype Server struct {
    30Ôćĺ	Name        string `json:"name,omitempty"`
    31Ôćĺ	ID          int
    32Ôćĺ	Enabled     bool
    33Ôćĺ	users       []string // not exported
    34Ôćĺ	http.Server          // embedded
    35Ôćĺ}
    36Ôćĺ
    37Ôćĺserver := &Server{
    38Ôćĺ	Name:    "gopher",
    39Ôćĺ	ID:      123456,
    40Ôćĺ	Enabled: true,
    41Ôćĺ}
    42Ôćĺ```
    43Ôćĺ
    44Ôćĺ```go
    45Ôćĺ// Convert a struct to a map[string]interface{}
    46Ôćĺ// => {"Name":"gopher", "ID":123456, "Enabled":true}
    47Ôćĺm := structs.Map(server)
    48Ôćĺ
    49Ôćĺ// Convert the values of a struct to a []interface{}
    50Ôćĺ// => ["gopher", 123456, true]
    51Ôćĺv := structs.Values(server)
    52Ôćĺ
    53Ôćĺ// Convert the names of a struct to a []string
    54Ôćĺ// (see "Names methods" for more info about fields)
    55Ôćĺn := structs.Names(server)
    56Ôćĺ
    57Ôćĺ// Convert the values of a struct to a []*Field
    58Ôćĺ// (see "Field methods" for more info about fields)
    59Ôćĺf := structs.Fields(server)
    60Ôćĺ
    61Ôćĺ// Return the struct name => "Server"
    62Ôćĺn := structs.Name(server)
    63Ôćĺ
    64Ôćĺ// Check if any field of a struct is initialized or not.
    65Ôćĺh := structs.HasZero(server)
    66Ôćĺ
    67Ôćĺ// Check if all fields of a struct is initialized or not.
    68Ôćĺz := structs.IsZero(server)
    69Ôćĺ
    70Ôćĺ// Check if server is a struct or a pointer to struct
    71Ôćĺi := structs.IsStruct(server)
    72Ôćĺ```
    73Ôćĺ
    74Ôćĺ### Struct methods
    76ÔćĺThe structs functions can be also used as independent methods by creating a new
    77Ôćĺ`*structs.Struct`. This is handy if you want to have more control over the
    78Ôćĺstructs (such as retrieving a single Field).
    79Ôćĺ
    80Ôćĺ```go
    81Ôćĺ// Create a new struct type:
    82Ôćĺs := structs.New(server)
    83Ôćĺ
    84Ôćĺm := s.Map()              // Get a map[string]interface{}
    85Ôćĺv := s.Values()           // Get a []interface{}
    86Ôćĺf := s.Fields()           // Get a []*Field
    87Ôćĺn := s.Names()            // Get a []string
    88Ôćĺf := s.Field(name)        // Get a *Field based on the given field name
    89Ôćĺf, ok := s.FieldOk(name)  // Get a *Field based on the given field name
    90Ôćĺn := s.Name()             // Get the struct name
    91Ôćĺh := s.HasZero()          // Check if any field is uninitialized
    92Ôćĺz := s.IsZero()           // Check if all fields are uninitialized
    93Ôćĺ```
    94Ôćĺ
    95Ôćĺ### Field methods
    97ÔćĺWe can easily examine a single Field for more detail. Below you can see how we
    98Ôćĺget and interact with various field methods:
    99Ôćĺ
   100Ôćĺ
   101Ôćĺ```go
   102Ôćĺs := structs.New(server)
   103Ôćĺ
   104Ôćĺ// Get the Field struct for the "Name" field
   105Ôćĺname := s.Field("Name")
   106Ôćĺ
   107Ôćĺ// Get the underlying value,  value => "gopher"
   108Ôćĺvalue := name.Value().(string)
   109Ôćĺ
   110Ôćĺ// Set the field's value
   111Ôćĺname.Set("another gopher")
   112Ôćĺ
   113Ôćĺ// Get the field's kind, kind =>  "string"
   114Ôćĺname.Kind()
   115Ôćĺ
   116Ôćĺ// Check if the field is exported or not
   117Ôćĺif name.IsExported() {
   118Ôćĺ	fmt.Println("Name field is exported")
   119Ôćĺ}
   120Ôćĺ
   121Ôćĺ// Check if the value is a zero value, such as "" for string, 0 for int
   122Ôćĺif !name.IsZero() {
   123Ôćĺ	fmt.Println("Name is initialized")
   124Ôćĺ}
   125Ôćĺ
   126Ôćĺ// Check if the field is an anonymous (embedded) field
   127Ôćĺif !name.IsEmbedded() {
   128Ôćĺ	fmt.Println("Name is not an embedded field")
   129Ôćĺ}
   130Ôćĺ
   131Ôćĺ// Get the Field's tag value for tag name "json", tag value => "name,omitempty"
   132ÔćĺtagValue := name.Tag("json")
   133Ôćĺ```
   134Ôćĺ
   135ÔćĺNested structs are supported too:
   136Ôćĺ
   137Ôćĺ```go
   138ÔćĺaddrField := s.Field("Server").Field("Addr")
   139Ôćĺ
   140Ôćĺ// Get the value for addr
   141Ôćĺa := addrField.Value().(string)
   142Ôćĺ
   143Ôćĺ// Or get all fields
   144ÔćĺhttpServer := s.Field("Server").Fields()
   145Ôćĺ```
   146Ôćĺ
   147ÔćĺWe can also get a slice of Fields from the Struct type to iterate over all
   148Ôćĺfields. This is handy if you wish to examine all fields:
   149Ôćĺ
   150Ôćĺ```go
   151Ôćĺs := structs.New(server)
   152Ôćĺ
   153Ôćĺfor _, f := range s.Fields() {
   154Ôćĺ	fmt.Printf("field name: %+v\n", f.Name())
   155Ôćĺ
   156Ôćĺ	if f.IsExported() {
   157Ôćĺ		fmt.Printf("value   : %+v\n", f.Value())
   158Ôćĺ		fmt.Printf("is zero : %+v\n", f.IsZero())
   159Ôćĺ	}
   160Ôćĺ}
   161Ôćĺ```
   162Ôćĺ
